ive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313183122/http://legacy.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20050320/news_1n20ponyexp.html |archive-date=March 13, 2012 |url-status=dead }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |url=//archive.org/details/ponyexpressstati00fike |title=The Pony Express Stations of Utah in Historical Perspective |last=Fike |first=Richard E. |last2=Headley |first2=Joh W. |publisher=Bureau of Land Management, Utah |year=1979|location=Washington, D.C. |last-author-amp= yes }}\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924030134104 |title=The Postage Stamps of the United States |last=Luff |first=John Nicholas |publisher=Scott Stamp & Coin Company |year= 1902}}\n* {{cite book |url=//archive.org/stream/athrillingandtr01vissgoog#page/n8/mode/2up |title=A Thrilling and Truthful History of the Pony Express: Or, Blazing the Westward Way |last=Visscher |first=William Lightfoot |publisher=Rand McNally |year=1908}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sister project links}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170825004513/http://spiritoftheponyexpress.com/ Spirit of the Pony Express] (Documentary)\n* [http://www.nps.gov/poex/index.htm Pony Express National Historic Trail] (National Park Service)\n* [https://www.blm.gov/programs/national-conservation-lands/pony-express Pony Express National Historic Trail] (Bureau of Land Management)\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf409nb3f6/ |title=Inventory of the Waddell F. Smith Papers,1939\u20131976 |publisher=[[Online Archive of California]]}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.historybuff.com/library/refrichardson.html |title=The Correct Identity of Billy Richardson, the Pony Express Rider |last=Hartnagle |first=Ernie |last2=Hartnagle |first2=Elaine |last-author-amp=yes |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509192608/http://www.historybuff.com/library/refrichardson.html |archivedate=May 9, 2008 }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.kansastravel.org/hollenbergstation.htm |title=Hollenberg Pony Express Station |publisher=kansastravel.org}}\n* [http://briankeithohara.blogspot.com/2013/02/billy-tate-pony-express-rider-and-hero.html The True Story of Billy Tate Pony Express Rider Who died at 14-years-old]\n* [https://www.visittheusa.com/experience/pony-express-national-historic-trail Visit the USA]\n{{Commons category-inline|Pony Express}}\n\n{{TrailSystem}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1860 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:1860 in the United States]]\n[[Category:1861 disestablishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:1861 in the United States]]\n[[Category:19th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American folklore]]\n[[Category:American frontier]]\n[[Category:Central Overland Route]]\n[[Category:Express mail]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1849\u20131865)]]\n[[Category:History of United States expansionism]]\n[[Category:Historic trails and roads in California]]\n[[Category:Historic trails and roads in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Historic trails and roads in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Historic trails and roads in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Historic trails and roads in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Historic trails and roads in Utah]]\n[[Category:Historic trails and roads in Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Lincoln Highway]]\n[[Category:National Historic Trails of the United States]]\n[[Category:Pony Express| ]]\n[[Category:Postal history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Trails and roads in the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Units of the National Landscape Conservation System]]\n[[Category:Utah War]]\n[[Category:Wells Fargo]]\n", "name_user": "Steven Skaggs", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar: \"Bringing with it was\" to \"With it was\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pony_Express"}
{"title_page": "Gary Wright", "text_new": "{{About||the former mayor of New Denver, British Columbia|Gary Wright (politician)|the racing driver|Gary Wright (racing driver)|the ice hockey coach|Gary Wright (ice hockey)}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Gary Wright\n| image            = 20110626 073 All-Starr-Band-in-Paris Gary-Wright keyboards WP.jpg\n| image_size =275\n| caption          = Wright performing in 2011\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Gary Malcolm Wright\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1943|4|26}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cresskill, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| instrument       = [[Vocals]], [[Electronic keyboard|keyboards]]<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Hard rock]]|[[progressive rock]]|[[soft rock]]|[[world music]]|[[New-age music|new age]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|musician|composer}}\n| label            = [[20th Century Fox Records|20th Century Fox]], [[Island Records|Island]], [[A&M Records|A&M]], [[Ariola Records|Ariola]], Goodear, [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]], [[Cypress Records|Cypress]], Triloka/Worldly, High Wave Music, Larkio\n| years_active     = 1960\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = [[Spooky Tooth]], Wonderwheel, [[George Harrison]], [[Ringo Starr & His All-Starr Band]]\n}}\n\n'''Gary Malcolm Wright''' (born April 26, 1943) is an American singer, songwriter, musician, and composer best known for his 1976 hit songs \"[[Dream Weaver]]\" and \"[[Love Is Alive (Gary Wright song)|Love Is Alive]]\", and for his role in helping establish the [[synthesizer]] as a leading instrument in rock and pop music. Wright's breakthrough album, ''[[The Dream Weaver]]'' (1975), came after he had spent seven years in London as, alternately, a member of the British [[hard rock|heavy rock]] band [[Spooky Tooth]] and a solo artist on [[A&M Records]]. While in England, he played keyboards on former [[The Beatles|Beatle]] [[George Harrison]]'s triple album ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'' (1970), so beginning a friendship that inspired the [[Indian religions|Indian]] religious themes and spirituality inherent in Wright's subsequent songwriting. His work since the late 1980s has embraced [[world music]] and the [[New-age music|new age]] genre, although none of his post-1976 releases has matched the popularity of ''The Dream Weaver''.\n\nA former child actor, Wright performed on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in the hit musical ''[[Fanny (musical)|Fanny]]'' before studying medicine and then psychology in New York and Berlin. After meeting [[Chris Blackwell]] of [[Island Records]] in Europe, Wright moved to London, where he helped establish Spooky Tooth as a popular live act. He also served as the band's principal songwriter on their recordings \u2013 among them, the well-regarded albums ''[[Spooky Two]]'' (1969) and ''[[You Broke My Heart So I Busted Your Jaw]]'' (1973). His solo album ''[[Footprint (album)|Footprint]]'' (1971), recorded with contributions from Harrison, coincided with the formation of Wright's short-lived band Wonderwheel, which included guitarist [[Mick Jones (Foreigner)|Mick Jones]]. Also during the early 1970s, Wright played on notable recordings by [[B.B. King]], [[Jerry Lee Lewis]], [[Ringo Starr]], [[Harry Nilsson]] ,[[Johnny Hallyday]] and [[Ronnie Spector]], while his musical association with Harrison endured until shortly before the latter's death in 2001.\n\nWright turned to [[film soundtrack]] work in the early 1980s, which led to him re-recording his most popular song, \"Dream Weaver\", for the 1992 comedy ''[[Wayne's World (film)|Wayne's World]]''. Following Spooky Tooth's reunion tour in 2004, Wright has performed live frequently, either as a member of Starr's [[Ringo Starr & His All-Starr Band|All-Starr Band]], with his own live band, or on subsequent Spooky Tooth reunions. Wright's most recent solo albums, including ''Waiting to Catch the Light'' (2008) and ''Connected'' (2010), have all been issued on his Larklio record label. In 2014, [[TarcherPerigee|Jeremy P. Tarcher]] published his autobiography, titled ''Dream Weaver: Music, Meditation, and My Friendship with George Harrison''.\n\n==Early life==\nGary Wright was born and raised in [[Cresskill, New Jersey|Cresskill]], New Jersey.<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright|author= Ankeny, Jason|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/gary-wright-mn0000191006/biography|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 1, 2014}}</ref> A child actor, he made his TV debut at the age of seven, on the show ''[[Captain Video and His Video Rangers]]'', filmed in New York.<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\">''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', p. 1094.</ref> Among other acting work, he appeared in TV and radio commercials, before being offered a part in the 1954 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of the musical ''[[Fanny (musical)|Fanny]]''.<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\" /> Wright played the role of Cesario, the son of Fanny, who was played by future ''[[The Brady Bunch|Brady Bunch]]'' matriarch [[Florence Henderson]].<ref name=\"Smashing\">{{cite web|url=http://smashinginterviews.com/interviews/musicians/gary-wright-interview-the-dream-weaver-gets-connected-tours-with-ringo-starr|title=Gary Wright Interview: The 'Dream Weaver' Gets 'Connected,' Tours with Ringo Starr|last=Parker|first=Melissa|publisher=Smashing Interviews|date=September 28, 2010|accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref> He spent two years with the production, during which he performed with Henderson on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]''.<ref name=\"TheSound\" />\n\nHaving studied piano and organ,<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\" /> Wright led various local rock bands while attending high school<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /> at [[Tenafly High School|Tenafly, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|url= |title=Music Notes |work=[[The Star-Ledger]] |date=November 16, 2000 |page=71|quote=Singer-songwriter-keyboardist Gary Wright, who grew up in Cresskill and went to Tenafly High School, will perform in New York tonight for the first time in 20 years.}}</ref><ref name=\"Voger/Hippiefest\" /> In 1959, he made his first commercial recording, with Billy Markle at [[NBC Radio]]'s New York studios.<ref name=\"Markle/GW\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright|author= Markle, Gil|url=http://www.studiowner.com/essays/essay.asp?books=0&pagnum=99|publisher=Diary of a Studio Owner|accessdate=March 1, 2014}}</ref> Credited to \"Gary & Billy\", the single \"Working After School\" was released on [[20th Century Fox Records]] in 1960.<ref name=\"Markle/GW\" />\n\nSeeing music as \"too unstable\" a career choice, as he later put it,<ref name=\"TheSound\" /> Wright studied to become a doctor at the [[College of William & Mary]] in Virginia and [[New York University]] before attending [[SUNY Downstate Medical Center|Downstate Medical College]] for a year,<ref name=\"Voger/Hippiefest\">{{cite web|last=Voger|first=Mark|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2011/07/hippiefest_gary_wright_intervi.html |title=Hippiefest: Gary Wright Interview |publisher=nj.com |date=July 29, 2011|accessdate=March 2, 2014 |page=}}</ref> all the while continuing to perform with local bands.<ref name=\"TheSound\" /><ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\">{{cite web|first=Shawn|last=Perry|url=http://vintagerock.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=32:gary-wright&catid=3:interviews&Itemid=4|title=The Gary Wright Interview |publisher=vintagerock.com|accessdate=March 2, 2014}}</ref> Having specialized in [[psychology]] in New York,<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\" /> he then went to [[West Germany]] in 1966<ref name=\"vonBF/dprp\">{{cite web|first=Menno|last=Von Brucken Fock|url=http://www.dprp.net/wp/interviews/?page_id=717|title=Interviews: Gary Wright |publisher=dprp.net|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> to complete his studies at the [[Free University of Berlin]].<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n===1967\u20131970: With Spooky Tooth===\nWright has described his initial musical influences as \"early [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]\" \u2013 namely, [[Ray Charles]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[James Brown]] and [[Bobby Bland]] \u2013 along with [[Rock and roll|rock 'n' roll]] artists [[Elvis Presley]] and [[Jerry Lee Lewis]], and [[the Beatles]].<ref name=\"TheSound\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright Interview (100.3 The Sound)|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-As9hdDoDOU|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=September 23, 2010|accessdate=March 2, 2014}}</ref> While in Europe in 1967, Wright abandoned his plans to become a doctor<ref name=\"TheSound\" /> and instead toured locally with a band he had formed, the New York Times.<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /> When the latter supported the English group [[Traffic (band)|Traffic]] \u2013 at Oslo in Norway, according to Wright<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" /> \u2013 he met [[Island Records]] founder [[Chris Blackwell]].<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /> Wright recalls that he and Blackwell had a mutual friend in [[Jimmy Miller]],<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" /> the New York-born [[record producer|producer]] of Island acts such as [[the Spencer Davis Group]] and Traffic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/10/24/obituaries/jimmy-miller-52-recording-producer.html |title=Jimmy Miller, 52, Recording Producer |work=[[The New York Times|New York Times]]|date=October 24, 1994|accessdate=March 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBlackwell invited Wright to London, where he joined English singer and pianist [[Mike Harrison (musician)|Mike Harrison]] and drummer [[Mike Kellie]] in their band Art (formerly [[The V.I.P.s (band)|the VIPs]]).<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 938\">''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', p. 938.</ref> The group soon changed its name to [[Spooky Tooth]],<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /> with Wright as joint lead vocalist<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" /> and [[Hammond organ]] player.<ref>Leng, pp. 90, 91.</ref> While noting the band's lack of significant commercial success over its career, ''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'' describes Spooky Tooth as \"a bastion of Britain's hard-rock scene\".<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 938\" />\n\nSpooky Tooth's first album was ''[[It's All About]]'', released on Island in June 1968.<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\" /> Produced by Miller,<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\" /> it contained the Wright-composed \"Sunshine Help Me\" and six songs he co-wrote with either Miller, Harrison or [[Luther Grosvenor]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Spooky Tooth ''It's All About''|author= Anderson, Jason|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r49908|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> the band's guitarist.<ref name=\"MusicHound p 1248\">Graff & Durchholz, p. 1248.</ref> ''[[Spooky Two]]'', often considered the band's best work, followed in March 1969, with Miller again producing.<ref name=\"MusicHound p 1249\">Graff & Durchholz, p. 1249.</ref> Wright composed or co-composed seven of the album's eight songs, including \"That Was Only Yesterday\" and \"[[Better By You, Better Than Me]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Spooky Tooth ''Spooky Two''|author= DeGagne, Mike|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/spooky-two-mw0000191912|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> ''Spooky Two'' sold well in America but, like ''It's All About'', it failed to place on the UK's top 40 albums chart.<ref name=\"Salewicz/LIR\" />\n\nThe third Spooky Tooth album was ''[[Ceremony (Spooky Tooth and Pierre Henry album)|Ceremony]]'', a Wright-instigated collaboration with French [[electronic music]] pioneer [[Pierre Henry]],<ref name=\"MusicHound p 1248\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Pierre Henry/Spooky Tooth ''Ceremony: An Electric Mass''|author= Allan, Mark|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/ceremony-an-electric-mass-mw0000599906|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> released in December 1969.<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 938\" /> Songwriting for all the tracks was credited to Henry and Wright,<ref name=\"Celebration sleeve\">[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=4622268 Sleeve and label credits], ''Celebration'' LP (US promo). [[A&M Records]], 1970; produced by Spooky Tooth & Pierre Henry.</ref> after the latter had passed the band's recordings on to Henry for what ''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia'' terms \"processed ''[[musique concr\u00e8te]]'' overdubs\".<ref>''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', pp. 938\u201339.</ref>\n\nAlthough Wright had traditionally provided an experimental influence within Spooky Tooth,<ref name=\"MusicHound p 1248\" /> he regretted the change of musical direction, saying in a 1973 interview: \"We should have really taken off after ''Spooky Two'' but we got into the absurd situation of letting Pierre Henry make the ''Ceremony'' album. Then he took it back to France and remixed it.\"<ref name=\"Salewicz/LIR\">Salewicz, Chris (February 1973). \"Spooky Tooth Together Again\". ''[[Let It Rock (magazine)|Let It Rock]]''. Available at [http://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/spooky-tooth-together-again Rock's Backpages] (''subscription required'').</ref> With bass player [[Greg Ridley]] having already left the band in 1969 to join [[Humble Pie (band)|Humble Pie]],<ref>''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', pp. 462, 938.</ref> Wright departed in January 1970 to pursue a solo career.<ref name=\"Salewicz/LIR\" />\n\n===1970\u20131972: Solo career on A&M Records, Wonderwheel, and London session work===\n\n====''Extraction''====\nAfter signing with [[A&M Records]], Wright recorded ''Extraction'' (1970) in London<ref name=\"Leng p 108\">Leng, p. 108.</ref> with musicians including Kellie, guitarist [[Hugh McCracken]], bassist [[Klaus Voormann]] and drummer [[Alan White (Yes drummer)|Alan White]].<ref name=\"AM/Extraction credits\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright ''Extraction'': Credits|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/extraction-mw0000460615/credits|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref> Wright co-produced the album with [[Andy Johns]],<ref name=\"AM/Extraction credits\" /> who had been the recording engineer on ''Spooky Two''<ref name=\"Spooky Two sleeve\">[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=3062838 Sleeve credits], ''Spooky Two'' LP. [[Island Records]], 1969; produced by Jimmy Miller.</ref> and ''Ceremony''.<ref name=\"Celebration sleeve\" /> The album included \"Get on the Right Road\", which was issued as a single, and \"The Wrong Time\",<ref name=\"WrightOnA&M\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright |author= |url=http://www.onamrecords.com/myartists.php?artist=Gary%20Wright|publisher=On A&M Records|accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref> co-written by Wright and McCracken.<ref>Sleeve credits, ''Extraction'' LP. ([[A&M Records]], 1970; produced by Gary Wright & Andy Johns).</ref>\n\n====George Harrison's ''All Things Must Pass''====\nThrough Voormann,<ref name=\"DailyBeast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/09/29/when-gary-wright-met-george-harrison-dream-weaver-john-and-yoko-and-more.html |title=When Gary Wright Met George Harrison: Dream Weaver, John and Yoko, and More|publisher=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=September 29, 2014 |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> Wright was invited to play piano on former Beatle [[George Harrison]]'s 1970 triple album ''[[All Things Must Pass]]''.<ref name=\"Smashing\" /><ref>Leng, p. 91.</ref> Among what author [[Nicholas Schaffner]] later described as \"a rock orchestra of almost symphonic proportions, whose credits read like a Who's Who of the music scene\",<ref>Schaffner, p. 142.</ref> Wright was one of the album's principal keyboard players, together with former [[Delaney & Bonnie]] organist [[Bobby Whitlock]].<ref>Leng, p. 82fn.</ref> During the sessions, Wright and Harrison established a long-lasting friendship,<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /><ref name=\"Rodriguez p 87\">Rodriguez, p. 87.</ref> based on music and their shared interest in Indian religion.<ref name=\"Smashing\" /><ref>Leng, pp. 91, 108, 124\u201325, 209.</ref> In a 2009 interview with vintagerock.com, Wright described Harrison as \"my spiritual mentor\";<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" /> author Robert Rodriguez writes of Wright's \"unique\" place among musicians with whom Harrison collaborated at this time, in that Wright was neither an established star nor a friend from the years before Harrison achieved fame as a Beatle, and nor was he a \"studio pro\".<ref name=\"Rodriguez p 88\">Rodriguez, p. 88.</ref>\n\nWright played on all of Harrison's subsequent solo albums during the 1970s,<ref name=\"Barnes Interview\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright Interview with Alan Barnes Part 1|author= Barnes, Alan|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FnN3Eo96JyI|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=December 4, 2010|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>Leng, pp. 125, 153, 182\u201383, 190, 209.</ref> as well as on other releases that the ex-Beatle produced for [[Apple Records]].<ref>Wright, p. 109.</ref> These included two hit singles by Harrison's former bandmate [[Ringo Starr]] over 1971\u201372, \"[[It Don't Come Easy]]\" and \"[[Back Off Boogaloo]]\", and a 1971 comeback single by ex-[[The Ronettes|Ronette]] [[Ronnie Spector]], \"[[Try Some, Buy Some]]\".<ref>Spizer, pp. 255, 294, 297\u201398.</ref>{{refn|group=nb|Wright recalls that he had been asked to play on [[John Lennon]]'s ''[[Imagine (John Lennon album)|Imagine]]'' album (1971), but he was unable to attend the sessions.<ref name=\"Smashing\" /><ref name=\"DailyBeast\" />}}\n\n====''Footprint''====\nGary Wright joins Micky Jones and works for french rock star [[Johnny Hallyday]]for whom he writes many songs on several albums. 2 of which he will later on put on his own album.\n To promote ''Extraction'', Wright formed the band Wonderwheel in April 1971,<ref name=\"Robinson/Spooky bio\">{{cite web|author=Robinson, Alan|title=Spooky Tooth Biography|url=http://www.spookytooth.sk/bio.html|publisher=spookytooth.sk|accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref> with a lineup comprising guitarist [[Jerry Donahue]] \u2013 soon replaced by [[Mick Jones (Foreigner)|Mick Jones]] \u2013 Archie Legget (bass) and [[Bryson Graham]] (drums).<ref>{{cite web|last=Terol|first=Miguel|url=http://www.oocities.org/sunsetstrip/Diner/2674/bgrah_b.htm |title=Bryson Graham |publisher=The Musicians' Olympus |date=September 17, 2001|accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>Wright, p. 98.</ref> Donahue was among the many musicians on Wright's second album, ''[[Footprint (album)|Footprint]]'' (1971),<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, p. 201.</ref> along with George Harrison and ''All Things Must Pass'' contributors such as Voormann, White, [[Jim Gordon (musician)|Jim Gordon]], [[Bobby Keys]] and [[John Barham]].<ref name=\"Leng p 108\" /><ref>Wright, pp. 97, 99.</ref> Produced by Wright, the album included \"Stand for Our Rights\", a call for social unity, partly inspired by the [[Vietnam War]],<ref>Liner notes, ''Best of Gary Wright: The Dream Weaver''. [[Rhino Records]], 1998; produced by Gary Wright, Gary Peterson & David McLees.</ref> \"Two Faced Man\" and \"Love to Survive\".<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, pp. 105\u201306.</ref> In November 1971, Wright and Wonderwheel performed \"Two Faced Man\" on ''[[The Dick Cavett Show]]'' in New York, with Harrison accompanying on [[slide guitar]].<ref name=\"Rodriguez pp 88, 319-20\">Rodriguez, pp. 88, 319\u201320.</ref>{{refn|group=nb|The performance, along with Harrison's interview with host [[Dick Cavett]], was issued by [[Shout! Factory]] in 2005 on the DVD ''The Dick Cavett Show \u2013 Rock Icons''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Galbraith IV|first=Stuart|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/17159/dick-cavett-show-rock-icons-the/ |title='''The Dick Cavett Show \u2013 Rock Icons'' |publisher=dvdtalk.com |date=August 16, 2005|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref>}} Wright has expressed gratitude for Harrison's support during this stage of his career, citing the ex-Beatle's uncredited production on ''Footprint''<ref name=\"Flucke/Popdose\">{{cite web|first=Mojo |last=Flucke |url=http://popdose.com/the-popdose-interview-gary-dream-weaver-wright/ |title=The Popdose Interview: Gary 'Dream Weaver' Wright|publisher=Popdose|date=April 3, 2009 |accessdate=March 6, 2015}}</ref> and his arranging the ''Dick Cavett Show'' appearance.<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" /> Despite this exposure,<ref name=\"Rodriguez pp 88, 319-20\" /> like ''Extraction'', the album failed to chart.<ref name=\"Leng p 108\" /><ref>Wright, pp. 99\u2013100.</ref>\n\nAmong other recordings over this period, Wright played piano on [[Harry Nilsson]]'s 1972 hit \"[[Without You (Badfinger song)|Without You]]\"<ref name=\"Rodriguez p 88\" /> and accompanied [[B.B. King]], Starr, Gordon, Voormann and others on ''[[B.B. King in London]]'' (1971),<ref>Randall, Brackett & Hoard, p. 453.</ref> which included Wright's composition \"Wet Hayshark\".<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, p. 105.</ref> He later participated in London sessions by Jerry Lee Lewis,<ref name=\"Barnes Interview\" /> issued as the double album ''The Session'' (1973).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jerry Lee Lewis ''The Session''|author=Unterberger, Richie |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-session-mw0000650415|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref> Wright also produced an eponymous album by [[folk rock]] band Howl the Good,<ref>{{cite web|title=Credits: Howl the Good ''Howl the Good'' |author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/howl-the-good-mw0000880367/credits|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> released on the Rare Earth label.<ref>{{cite web|title=Howl the Good \u2013 Howl the Good (Vinyl, LP, Album)|author= |url=http://www.discogs.com/Howl-The-Good-Howl-The-Good/release/3571421|publisher=[[Discogs]]|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====''Ring of Changes''====\nIn 1972, Wright moved to [[Devon]] with Wonderwheel to work on songs for a new album, titled ''Ring of Changes''. With Tom Duffey having replaced Leggett on bass, the band recorded the songs at [[Olympic Studios|Olympic]] and [[Apple Studio|Apple]] studios in London.<ref>Wright, pp. 112\u201313.</ref> After issuing \"I Know\" as an advance single,<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=4559345 Sleeve text], \"Ring of Changes\" promotional single. [[A&M Records]], 1972; produced by Gary Wright.</ref> A&M chose to cancel the album.<ref name=\"Wright p 113\">Wright, p. 113.</ref>{{refn|group=nb|While ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' lists ''Ring of Changes'' as a 1972 release,<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\" /> A&M's archives site suggests that the album may have been withdrawn.<ref name=\"WrightOnA&M\" />}} Wright also wrote the soundtrack for a film by former [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] skier [[Willy Bogner Jr.|Willy Bogner]], ''Benjamin'' (1972),<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Wright \u2013 Benjamin \u2013 The Original Soundtrack of Willy Bogner's Motion Picture (Vinyl, LP, Album)|url=http://www.discogs.com/Gary-Wright-Benjamin-The-Original-Soundtrack-Of-Willy-Bogners-Motion-Picture/release/5256646|publisher=[[Discogs]]|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> from which the German label [[Ariola Records]] released \"Goodbye Sunday\" as a single that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Wright \u2013 Goodbye Sunday|url=http://www.discogs.com/Gary-Wright-Goodbye-Sunday/release/4094895|publisher=[[Discogs]]|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> The full soundtrack album, recorded with Jones, Leggett and Graham,<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=5256646 Sleeve credits], ''Benjamin \u2013 The Original Soundtrack of Willy Bogner's Motion Picture'' LP. [[Ariola Records]], 1974; produced by Willy Bogner.</ref> was issued by Ariola in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicknockout.net/Artists/wrightgary.html |title=Gary Wright|publisher=musicknockout.net |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618032130/http://www.musicknockout.net/Artists/wrightgary.html|archivedate=June 18, 2010 |accessdate=March 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1972, Wright decided to disband Wonderwheel and re-form Spooky Tooth.<ref name=\"Rosen/MW\">Rosen, Steven (November 1973). \"The Return of Spooky Tooth\". ''Music World''. Available at [http://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/the-return-of-spooky-tooth Rock's Backpages] (''subscription required'').</ref> Shortly before doing so, he participated in sessions for Harrison's ''[[Living in the Material World]]'' (1973),<ref>Leng, pp. 124\u201325.</ref> an album that Wright describes as \"a beautiful masterpiece\" and his favorite Harrison album.<ref>Wright, p. 107.</ref> Talking to [[Chris Salewicz]] of ''[[Let It Rock (magazine)|Let It Rock]]'' in early 1973, Wright explained his decision to abandon his solo career: \"I think my main talent is getting the music together and arranging it. I'm not a showman and so I couldn't be a [[Cat Stevens]] out front with just backing musicians, which I was expected to be with Wonderwheel.\"<ref name=\"Salewicz/LIR\" /> In his autobiography, however, Wright says that it was his disappointment at A&M's rejection of ''Ring of Changes'' that led him to contact Blackwell about re-forming Spooky Tooth.<ref name=\"Wright p 113\" />\n\n===1972\u20131974: Re-forms Spooky Tooth===\nThe only members from the original lineup, Wright and Mike Harrison relaunched Spooky Tooth with Jones and Graham from Wonderwheel, and Chris Stewart,<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 938\" /><ref name=\"MusicHound p 1248\" /> formerly the bassist with English singer [[Terry Reid]].<ref name=\"Salewicz/LIR\" /> Salewicz visited the band while they were recording at Island's [[Sarm West Studios|Notting Hill studio]] and remarked of Wright's role in the group, \"it is clear who is the leader of this brand of Spooky Tooth, and, I suspect, of the original, too\"; Salewicz described Wright as \"urbane, loquacious with the remnants of a New Jersey accent, and a touch of [[Dudley Moore]] about the face\".<ref name=\"Salewicz/LIR\" />\n\nOn their new album, ''[[You Broke My Heart So I Busted Your Jaw]]'' (1973),<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 938\" /> Wright composed six of the eight tracks, including \"Cotton Growing Man\", \"Wildfire\" and \"Self Seeking Man\", and co-wrote the remaining two.<ref name=\"You Broke sleeve\">[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=3568894 Label credits], ''You Broke My Heart So I Busted Your Jaw'' LP. [[Island Records]], 1973; produced by Gary Wright & Spooky Tooth.</ref> With the group's standing having been elevated since 1970 \u2013 a situation that music journalist Steven Rosen likened at the time to [[the Yardbirds]], [[the Move]] and other 1960s bands after their break-up<ref name=\"Rosen/MW\" /> \u2013 Spooky Tooth toured extensively to promote the album.<ref name=\"Robinson/Spooky bio\" /> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' reviewer [[Jon Tiven]] praised Wright's songwriting on ''You Broke My Heart'', adding: \"there is tremendous consistency to these originals&nbsp;... and 'Wildfire' is ample proof that Gary could have written for [[the Temptations]] if he really wanted to.\"<ref>Tiven, Jon (June 21, 1973). \"Spooky Tooth: ''You Broke My Heart So I Busted Your Jaw''\". ''[[Rolling Stone]]''. Available at [http://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/spooky-tooth-iyou-broke-my-heart-so-i-busted-your-jawi Rock's Backpages] (''subscription required'').</ref>\n\n{{quote box|quote= [We] could have definitely been like one of those bands, like [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]] and all those people who were our contemporaries. I think [Spooky Tooth] didn't have the steady momentum and upward drive. It stopped and started, broke up and then went back and broke up. It never really got enough behind it to really catapult it to success.<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" />|source= \u2013 Wright in 2009, reflecting on Spooky Tooth's lack of a commercial breakthrough|width=25%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\nThe band released a follow-up, ''[[Witness (Spooky Tooth album)|Witness]]'', in November 1973,<ref name=\"Robinson/Spooky bio\" /> by which point Graham had departed, with Mike Kellie returning on drums.<ref name=\"Rosen/MW\" /> By February 1974, Stewart and Harrison had also left.<ref name=\"Robinson/Spooky bio\" /> In January that year, Wright accompanied George Harrison to India,<ref>Wright, pp. 120\u201321, 123.</ref> where they journeyed to [[Varanasi]] (Benares), the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] spiritual capital of India, and home to Harrison's friend [[Ravi Shankar]].<ref name=\"Olivia p 258\">Olivia Harrison, p. 258.</ref> The visit would influence the spiritual quality of Wright's lyrics when he returned to his solo career.<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" />\n\nIn England, he and Harrison worked together on ''[[The Place I Love]]'' (1974),<ref>Leng, pp. 143, 144.</ref> the debut album by English duo [[Splinter (band)|Splinter]].<ref>Schaffner, p. 179.</ref><ref>Wight, pp. 109, 110.</ref> In addition to playing keyboards, Wright served as what author Simon Leng terms \"a sounding board and musical amanuensis\" on the project,<ref>Leng, p. 144.</ref> which was the first album released on Harrison's [[Dark Horse Records|Dark Horse]] record label.<ref>Castleman & Podrazik, pp. 200\u201301, 205\u201306, 311.</ref> Wright regrouped with Spooky Tooth for a final album, ''[[The Mirror (Spooky Tooth album)|The Mirror]]'' (1974), with [[Mike Patto]] as their new vocalist.<ref>''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', pp. 938, 939.</ref> Following further personnel changes, ''The Mirror'' was issued by Goodear Records in the UK in October 1974, a month after Wright had disbanded the group.<ref name=\"Robinson/Spooky bio\" />\n\n===1975\u20131981: Solo career on Warner Bros. Records===\n\n====''The Dream Weaver''====\nAfter Spooky Tooth's break-up, Wright returned to New Jersey and began compiling songs for his third solo album.<ref name=\"CC//MM\" /> Under the guidance of new manager [[Dee Anthony]], he chose to sign with [[Warner Bros. Records]], mainly because the company had no keyboard virtuosos among its other acts.<ref name=\"CC//MM\">Charlesworth, Chris (June 5, 1976). \"Gary Wright: Wright at Last\". ''[[Melody Maker]]''. Available at [http://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/gary-wright-wright-at-last Rock's Backpages] (''subscription required'').</ref> Wright says that it was while routining his songs with all his stage equipment set up \u2013 [[Hammond organ]], [[Clavinet|Hohner Clavinet]], [[Rhodes piano|Fender Rhodes]] electric piano, [[Minimoog]] and [[ARP String Ensemble]] \u2013 together with a [[drum machine]], that he decided to record the album \"all on keyboards\", without guitars.<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" /> He acknowledges that artists such as [[Stevie Wonder]] had similarly released keyboard-dominated music, but \"[Wonder] used brass and he used other things as well\".<ref name=\"Voger/Hippiefest\" /> On Wright's debut album for Warner Bros., ''[[The Dream Weaver]]'' (1975),<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\" /> he, [[David Foster]] and [[Bobby Lyle]] played a variety of keyboard instruments, supported only by drummers [[Jim Keltner]] and [[Andy Newmark]],<ref name=\"DreamWeaver/AM\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright ''The Dream Weaver'': Credits|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-dream-weaver-mw0000193346/credits|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 19, 2014}}</ref> apart from a guitar part on the track \"Power of Love\" by [[Ronnie Montrose]].<ref name=\"DreamWeaverSleeve\">[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=4923686 Sleeve credits], ''The Dream Weaver'' LP. [[Warner Bros. Records]], 1975; produced by Gary Wright.</ref> Jason Ankeny of [[AllMusic]] describes ''The Dream Weaver'' as \"one of the first [rock albums] created solely via synthesizer technology\".<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" />\n\n{{quote box|quote= I mean&nbsp;... I'm an overnight success in ten years, right? I've been through periods of self-doubt, wondering whether or not I wanted to stay an artist&nbsp;... but I guess, like in all things, it's timing. The right timing, the right songs and strong management at last.<ref name=\"CC//MM\" />|source= \u2013 Wright commenting in 1976 on the unexpected success of ''The Dream Weaver''|width=25%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\nThe album was issued in July 1975 and enjoyed minimal success in America until the release of its second single, \"[[Dream Weaver (song)|Dream Weaver]]\", in November.<ref name=\"CC//MM\" /> The song, which Wright had written on acoustic guitar<ref name=\"CC//MM\" /> after his visit to India with Harrison,<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Wright > Inspiration|author= |url=http://www.thedreamweaver.com|publisher=thedreamweaver.com|accessdate=March 19, 2014}}</ref> went on to peak at number 2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"BB singles\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright: Chart History|author= |url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/302637/gary-wright/chart|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|billboard.com]]|accessdate=March 19, 2014}}</ref> and number 1 on the ''[[Cash Box]]'' singles chart.<ref name=\"The Book of Golden Discs\" /> Wright's biggest hit, \"Dream Weaver\" sold over 1 million copies in the US and was awarded a [[music recording sales certification|gold disc]] by the [[RIAA]] in March 1976.<ref name=\"The Book of Golden Discs\">Murrells, p. 365.</ref> The album climbed to number 7 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"BB albums/AM\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright: Awards|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/gary-wright-mn0000191006/awards|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 19, 2014}}</ref> and was certified [[music recording sales certification|platinum]].<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\" /> \"[[Love Is Alive (Gary Wright song)|Love Is Alive]]\", originally the album's lead single,<ref name=\"CC//MM\" /> then hit number 2 on the Hot 100, and \"Made to Love You\" climbed to number 79.<ref name=\"BB singles\" /> Although this commercial success was not repeated in the UK, ''The Dream Weaver'' was a big seller in [[West Germany]],<ref name=\"CC//MM\" /> where, Wright says, Spooky Tooth had been \"the number one band\" during 1969.<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" />\n\nFollowing the album's release, Wright toured extensively with a band comprising three keyboard players and a drummer.<ref name=\"CC//MM\" /> His elder sister Lorna, also a professional singer, joined the tour band as his backing vocalist.<ref>Wright, p. 20.</ref> Subsidized by synthesizer manufacturers [[Moog Music|Moog]] and [[Oberheim Electronics|Oberheim]],<ref name=\"Voger/Hippiefest\" /> Wright became one of the first musicians to perform with a portable keyboard, in the style of [[Edgar Winter]].<ref name=\"CC//MM\" /> Shawn Perry of vintagerock.com credits Wright with being \"as responsible for the emergence of the synthesizer as a mainstream instrument as [[Keith Emerson]] and&nbsp;... [[Rick Wakeman]]\",<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" /> while Robert Rodriguez describes Wright as a pioneer in both \"the integration of synthesizers into [[analog recording]]s\" and the use of the keyboard\u2013guitar hybrid known as the [[keytar]].<ref name=\"Rodriguez p 88\" />\n\nAmong his live performances in 1976, Wright shared the bill with [[Yes (band)|Yes]] and [[Peter Frampton]] at the [[United States Bicentennial|US Bicentennial]] concert held at [[John F. Kennedy Stadium|JFK Stadium]], Philadelphia, playing to a crowd estimated at 120,000.<ref name=\"Welch//MM\">Welch, Chris (June 26, 1976). \"Yes, Peter Frampton, Gary Wright: JFK Stadium, Philadelphia\". ''[[Melody Maker]]''. Available at [http://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/yes-peter-frampton-gary-wright-jfk-stadium-philadelphia Rock's Backpages] (''subscription required'').</ref> Wright then supported Frampton on a European tour, by which time a fourth keyboard player had been added to the band.<ref name=\"Salewicz/NME\">Salewicz, Chris (October 30, 1976). \"Peter Frampton: Empire Pool, Wembley, London\". ''[[NME]]''. Available at [http://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/peter-frampton-empire-pool-wembley-london Rock's Backpages] (''subscription required'').</ref> Amid this success, A&M issued ''That Was Only Yesterday'' (1976)<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 938\" /> \u2013 a compilation containing tracks from Wright's albums for the label and selections by Spooky Tooth<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Wright/Spooky Tooth \u2013 That Was Only Yesterday|author= |url=http://www.discogs.com/Gary-Wright-Spooky-Tooth-That-Was-Only-Yesterday/release/4498828|publisher=[[Discogs]]|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> \u2013 which charted at number 172 in America.<ref name=\"BB albums/AM\" />\n\n====''The Light of Smiles''====\nWright started recording his follow-up to ''The Dream Weaver'' in summer 1976, before which [[Chris Charlesworth]] of ''[[Melody Maker]]'' reported that it would be \"a logical development\" of its predecessor and \"again based entirely around what he can do with various types of keyboards\".<ref name=\"CC//MM\" /> Titled ''[[The Light of Smiles]]'' (1977), the album included \"I Am the Sky\", for which Wright gave a songwriting credit to the late Indian [[guru]] and [[Kriya Yoga]] teacher,<ref>Bowden, p. 629.</ref> [[Paramahansa Yogananda]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Wright ''The Light of Smiles''|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/light-of-smiles-mw0000532173|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 20, 2014}}</ref> The latter's poem \"The Light of Smiles\", taken from his book ''Metaphysical Meditations'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The Light of Smiles|url=http://lightworkers.org/node/193844|publisher=lightworkers.org|accessdate=March 20, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320205801/http://lightworkers.org/node/193844|archivedate=March 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> appeared on the inner sleeve to Wright's new album.<ref name=\"SmilesrInSleeve\">[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=1539260 Inner sleeve], ''The Light of Smiles'' LP. [[Warner Bros. Records]], 1977; produced by Gary Wright.</ref> Wright had acknowledged the guru as his inspiration for the title of ''The Dream Weaver'',<ref name=\"DreamWeaverSleeve\" /> and he later said of Yogananda's ''[[Autobiography of a Yogi]]'': \"It's a fantastic book and you won't want to put it down when you start reading it. Even, not from a spiritual point of view, but as a piece of literature, it's a total classic&nbsp;...\"<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" />\n\nProduced again by Wright, ''The Light of Smiles'' featured Wright, Foster, Peter Relich and others on a range of keyboard instruments, including Moog, Oberheim and ARP synthesizers, and drumming contributions from Art Wood and Keltner.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Wright ''The Light of Smiles'': Credits|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/light-of-smiles-mw0000532173/credits|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 20, 2014}}</ref> Issued by Warner Bros. in January 1977,<ref>{{cite web|title=Top Album Picks|author=Freedland, Nat (reviews ed.) |url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=pt-BR&id=YEUEAAAAMBAJ&q=gary+wright#v=snippet&q=gary%20wright&f=false|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 15, 1977|accessdate=March 20, 2014|page=80}}</ref> neither the album nor its lead single, \"Phantom Writer\", matched the popularity of Wright's earlier releases for the label.<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /> On the US ''Billboard'' charts, ''The Light of Smiles'' climbed to number 23,<ref name=\"BB albums/AM\" /> while \"Phantom Writer\" peaked at number 43.<ref name=\"BB singles\" />\n\n====''Touch and Gone'', ''Headin' Home'' and ''The Right Place''====\nWright continued to record albums for Warner Bros. until 1981, with only limited commercial success.<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /> Released in late 1977, ''[[Touch and Gone]]'' charted at number 117 in America,<ref name=\"BB albums/AM\" /> with its title track reaching number 73.<ref name=\"BB singles\" /> ''[[Headin' Home (album)|Headin' Home]]'', which AllMusic's Joe Viglione describes as \"an album seemingly driven by a serious relationship in crisis\",<ref name=\"Viglione/Home\" /> peaked at number 147 in 1979.<ref name=\"BB albums/AM\" /> In between these two albums, Wright played on \"[[If You Believe (George Harrison song)|If You Believe]]\", a song he co-wrote with Harrison in England on New Year's Day 1978,<ref>George Harrison, p. 358.</ref> which appeared on Harrison's [[George Harrison (album)|eponymous 1979 album]].<ref>Leng, pp. 199, 209.</ref>\n\nWright's last chart success in America was in 1981,<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\" /> when his album ''The Right Place'', co-produced with [[Dean Parks]],<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=1643529 Label credits], ''The Right Place'' LP. [[Warner Bros. Records]], 1981; produced by Gary Wright & Dean Parks.</ref> climbed to number 79.<ref name=\"BB albums/AM\" /> The single \"[[Really Wanna Know You]]\", which Wright co-wrote with Scottish singer [[Ali Thomson]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Ali Thomson|author=Stone, Doug |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/ali-thomson-mn0000004047|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> peaked at number 16 that year.<ref name=\"BB singles\" /> A second single from the album, \"Heartbeat\", appeared on ''Billboard''{{'}}s [[Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles|Bubbling Under]] listings, at number 107.<ref>{{cite web|title=Songs that charted under the Hot 100: 1981|author=|url=http://rateyourmusic.com/list/genesis16/songs_that_charted_under_the_hot_100__1981/|publisher=rateyourmusic.com|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===1982\u20132000: Film soundtracks and world music===\nWright's subsequent releases focused on film soundtracks and forays into [[world music]].<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /> After writing the score for [[Alan Rudolph]]'s 1982 thriller ''[[Endangered Species (1982 film)|Endangered Species]]'',<ref name=\"DreamWeaverBio\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright > Biography|author= |url=http://www.thedreamweaver.com|publisher=thedreamweaver.com|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> he supplied the soundtrack to another skiing-themed movie by Willy Bogner,<ref>{{cite web|title=Willy Bogner Film: Action Videos & Sport Movies|url=http://en.bogner.com/Discover/Willy-Bogner-Film|publisher=bogner.com|accessdate=March 21, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401162616/http://en.bogner.com/Discover/Willy-Bogner-Film|archivedate=April 1, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[Fire and Ice (1986 film)|Fire and Ice]]'' (1986), which hit number 1 on the German albums chart.<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /> Wright also contributed the song \"Hold on to Your Vision\" to the soundtrack of ''[[Cobra (1986 film)|Cobra]]'', a 1986 [[Action film|action movie]] starring [[Sylvester Stallone]].<ref name=\"Wright/Largo\">{{cite web|title=City of Largo, Florida / Events Calendar / Gary Wright|author=|url=http://www.largo.com/egov/apps/events/calendar.egov?view=detail;id=9133|publisher=largo.com|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAmong notable cover versions of Wright's songs during this period, [[Chaka Khan]] recorded \"Love Is Alive\" (retitled \"My Love Is Alive\") for her 1984 album ''[[I Feel for You (album)|I Feel for You]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Chaka Khan ''I Feel for You''|author=Henderson, Alex|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/i-feel-for-you-mw0000650354|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> which became an RIAA-certified million-seller.<ref>''The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll'', p. 536.</ref> A cover of his Spooky Tooth composition \"Better By You, Better Than Me\", by English [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Judas Priest]], was at the center of a 1990 court case regarding [[subliminal message]]s in song lyrics, after two [[Nevada]]n teenagers had enacted a [[suicide pact]] five years before.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scientific Consensus and Expert Testimony: Lessons from the Judas Priest Trial|author=Moore, Thomas E.|url=http://www.csicop.org/si/show/scientific_consensus_and_expert_testimony|publisher=csicop.org|date=November\u2013December 1996|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> From 1989 through to the late 1990s, [[Sampling (music)|samples]] of Wright's \"Dream Weaver\", \"Love Is Alive\" and \"Can't Find the Judge\" variously featured in songs by popular [[Rap music|rap]] and [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] artists [[Tone L\u014dc]], [[Dream Warriors (band)|Dream Warriors]], [[3rd Bass]] and [[M\u00fda]].<ref name=\"WhoSample\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright Music Sampled by Others|author=|url=http://www.whosampled.com/Gary-Wright/sampled/|publisher=whosampled.com|accessdate=March 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWright himself re-recorded \"Dream Weaver\" for the 1992 comedy ''[[Wayne's World (film)|Wayne's World]]'',<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /> the soundtrack album for which topped the US charts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Original Soundtrack ''Wayne's World'': Awards|author=|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/waynes-world-mw0000273867/awards|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> The song has since appeared in the films ''[[The People vs. Larry Flynt]]'' (1996) and ''[[Toy Story 3]]'' (2010).<ref name=\"Wright/Largo\" /> He later provided \"We Can Fly\" for another Bogner film, ''Ski to the Max'',<ref name=\"UtopiaArtists\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright Bio|author=|url=http://www.utopiaartists.com/bio_gary_wright.htm|publisher=utopiaartists.com|accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref> released in [[IMAX]] cinemas in October 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ski to the Max|url=https://www.imax.com/movies/m/ski-to-the-max/|publisher=imax.com|accessdate=March 25, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325191402/https://www.imax.com/movies/m/ski-to-the-max/|archivedate=March 25, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====''Who I Am'', ''First Signs of Life'' and ''Human Love''====\nIn 1988, Wright released ''Who I Am'' on A&M-distributed<ref>{{cite web|title=Cypress Records|author=|url=http://www.onamrecords.com/Cypress_Records.html|publisher=On A&M Records|date=|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> [[Cypress Records]].<ref name=\"New RS Encyclopedia p 1094\" /> Among the album's contributors were Western musicians such as Harrison, White and Keltner,<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Wright ''Who I Am'': Credits|author=|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/who-i-am-mw0000196319/credits|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> a group of [[Carnatic music|South Indian]] percussionists,<ref name=\"UtopiaArtists\" /> and [[Indian classical music|Indian classical]] violinists [[L. Subramaniam]] and [[L. Shankar]].<ref name=\"Wright bio/AM\" /> The previous year, Wright had contributed to Harrison's album ''[[Cloud Nine (George Harrison album)|Cloud Nine]]'' (1987), for which he co-wrote \"[[That's What It Takes]]\" with Harrison and [[Jeff Lynne]],<ref>Leng, pp. 248, 249.</ref> and played keyboards on songs such as \"[[When We Was Fab]]\".<ref>Kordosh, J. (December 1987). \"Fab! Gear! The George Harrison Interview (part 1)\". ''[[Creem]]''. Available at [http://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/the-return-of-spooky-tooth Rock's Backpages] (''subscription required'').</ref> One of the tracks from ''Who I Am'', \"Blind Alley\", was used in the 1988 horror film ''[[Spellbinder (film)|Spellbinder]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ringostrack.com/en/movie/spellbinder/43198 |title=Spellbinder Soundtrack (1988) OST |publisher=ringostrack.com |accessdate=December 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWright's next solo album was ''First Signs of Life'' (1995), recorded in Rio de Janeiro and at his own<ref name=\"vonBF/dprp\" /> High Wave Studios in Los Angeles,<ref name=\"First SignsSleeve\">Album booklet, ''First Signs of Life'' CD. Triloka/Worldly, 1995; produced by Gary Wright & Franz Pusch.</ref> and issued on the Triloka/Worldly record label.<ref name=\"MusicHound p 1249\" /><ref name=\"Discog/GW site\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright > Discography|author= |url=http://www.thedreamweaver.com|publisher=thedreamweaver.com|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> The album combined [[Music of Brazil|Brazilian]] rhythms<ref name=\"MusicHound p 1249\" /> with elements of African vocal tradition, creating what AllMusic's reviewer describes as \"an infectious [[worldbeat]] hybrid\", where \"the musicians' performances radiate sincerity and joy\".<ref name=\"AM/First Signs\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright ''First Signs of Life''|author=|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/first-signs-of-life-mw0000172265|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> ''First Signs of Life'' featured guest appearances from drummer [[Terry Bozzio]], Brazilian guitarist [[Ricardo Silveira]] and Harrison.<ref name=\"AM/First Signs\" /> The song \"Don't Try to Own Me\", co-written with Duane Hitchings, was later included on [[Rhino Records]]' ''Best of Gary Wright: The Dream Weaver'' \u2013 a 1998 compilation spanning his solo career from 1970 onwards, and featuring extensive liner notes by Wright.<ref name=\"AM/Best of GW\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright ''Best of Gary Wright: The Dream Weaver''|author=Stone, Doug|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/best-of-gary-wright-the-dream-weaver-mw0000043475|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''Human Love'' (1999) included new versions of \"Wildfire\" and \"The Wrong Time\",<ref name=\"AM/Human Love\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright ''Human Love''|author=|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/human-love-mw0000103074|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 22, 2014}}</ref> as well as \"If You Believe in Heaven\", a song written with [[Graham Gouldman]] that had first appeared on ''Best of Gary Wright''.<ref name=\"AM/Best of GW\" /> The album was co-produced by German world-music producer [[Marlon Klein]]<ref name=\"HumanLoveSleeve\" /> and released on the High Wave Music label.<ref name=\"Discog/GW site\" /><ref name=\"AM/Human Love\" /> Contributors to the sessions, held at High Wave and at Exil Musik in [[Bielefeld]], included [[Hindustani classical music|Hindustani classical]] vocalist [[Lakshmi Shankar]], Lynne and German composer [[Roman Bunka]].<ref name=\"HumanLoveSleeve\">Album booklet, ''Human Love'' CD. High Wave Music, 1999; produced by Gary Wright, Marlon Klein, Bernhart Locker & Franz Pusch.</ref>\n\n===Later career===\nHaving dedicated much of his time during the 1990s to his family, Wright subsequently resumed a more active musical career, starting with Spooky Tooth's 2004 reunion.<ref name=\"vonBF/dprp\" /> Their album and DVD ''Nomad Poets Live in Germany'' (2007) features Wright, Mike Harrison and Kellie from the band's original lineup.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spooky Tooth ''Nomad Poets Live in Germany''|author=|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/nomad-poets-live-in-germany-mw0000485207|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> Wright's past work has continued to inspire rap and dance tracks in the 21st century; samples of \"Heartbeat\" appear in songs by [[Jay-Z]] and [[Diam's]], while [[Pulsedriver|Topmodelz]] covered the song in 2007.<ref name=\"WhoSample\" /> Other artists who have used samples from Wright's 1975\u201381 recordings include [[Dilated Peoples]], [[Atmosphere (music group)|Atmosphere]], [[Infamous Mobb]], [[T.I.]] and [[Armand Van Helden]],<ref name=\"WhoSample\" /> the last of whom incorporated part of \"Comin' Apart\" (from ''The Right Place'') in his 2004 [[nightclub|club]] hit \"[[My My My (Armand Van Helden song)|My My My]]\".<ref name=\"DreamWeaverBio\" /> In addition, [[Eminem]] used \"interpolations\" from Spooky Tooth's \"Self Seeking Man\" in his song \"Spend Some Time\" (released on ''[[Encore (Eminem album)|Encore]]'' in 2004).<ref>Album notes, ''Encore'' CD. [[Aftermath Entertainment]], 2004; produced by Dr. Dre, Eminem, Luis Resto, Mike Elizondo & Mark Batson.</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2008, Wright joined [[Ringo Starr & His All-Starr Band]] for a North American tour, with Edgar Winter also in the lineup.<ref name=\"RingoSiteBio\">{{cite web|last=|first= |url=http://www.ringostarr.com/biography/ |title=Biography |publisher=ringostarr.com |date= |accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> The All-Starr Band's album and DVD ''[[Live at the Greek Theatre 2008]]'' (2010) includes Wright's performance of \"Dream Weaver\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-at-the-greek-theatre-2008-mw0002013992 |title=Ringo Starr & His All Starr Band ''Live at the Greek Theatre 2008'' |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |date= |accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> Wright later described the tour as \"a lot of fun\" and \"a big boost\" for his career.<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" />\n\n====''Waiting to Catch the Light'' and ''Connected''====\nTwo solo releases by Wright followed in late 2008, including the [[New-age music|new-age]] album ''Waiting to Catch the Light''.<ref name=\"vonBF/dprp\" /> A collection of instrumental pieces from \"several years\" before, he describes it as \"an atmospheric, [[ambient music]] kind of an album\", performed on \"vintage analog synthesizers&nbsp;... all [recorded] on analog tape\".<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" /> Also issued on Larkio,<ref name=\"Discog/GW site\" /> Wright's own record label,<ref name=\"vonBF/dprp\" /> the [[Extended play|EP]] ''The Light of a Million Suns'' consisted of unreleased tracks from his previous album projects, together with a new version of \"Love Is Alive\", sung by his son Dorian.<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" />\n\n[[File:Gary Wright, Everett, WA USA 2016-10-14.jpg|thumb|right|Wright performing in 2016]]\nIn May 2009, Wright rejoined Spooky Tooth to participate in a series of London concerts celebrating the 50th anniversary of Island Records' founding,<ref>{{cite web|title=Island Records 50th Anniversary \u2013 A Celebration|author= |url=http://earbender.com/2009/05/27/island-records-50th-anniversary-a-celebration/|publisher=earbender.com|accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref> before performing further shows with the band in Germany.<ref name=\"Perry/VintageR\" /> In June the following year, he released the album ''Connected'',<ref name=\"Smashing\" /> which marked a return to his more pop- and rock-oriented sound of the 1970s.<ref name=\"vonBF/dprp\" /><ref name=\"Greco/VintageR\" /> Starr, [[Joe Walsh]] and [[Jeff \"Skunk\" Baxter]] made guest appearances on the track \"Satisfied\",<ref name=\"Greco/VintageR\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright ''Connected'' \u2013 CD Review|author= Greco, Ralph Jr.|url=http://www.vintagerock.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=528:connected-gary-wright&catid=8:new-studio-releases&Itemid=38|publisher=vintagerock.com|accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref> which Wright co-wrote with songwriter [[Boyce and Hart|Bobby Hart]].<ref name=\"vonBF/dprp\" /> As a posthumous tribute to his friend George Harrison, the Deluxe Digital Edition of ''Connected'' included \"Never Give Up\",<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Wright \u2013 Connected (Deluxe Digital Edition) (File, Album)|author= |url=http://www.discogs.com/Gary-Wright-Connected-Deluxe-Digital-Edition/release/3660793|publisher=[[Discogs]]|accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref> which he and Harrison recorded in 1989, while the [[iTunes]] version added \"To Discover Yourself\", a song that the two musicians wrote together in 1971.<ref name=\"Greco/VintageR\" /> Wright recorded the latter song on the day of Harrison's death in November 2001.<ref name=\"Smashing\" /><ref name=\"Greco/VintageR\" /> He also contributed to [[Martin Scorsese]]'s 2011 documentary ''[[George Harrison: Living in the Material World]]''<ref>End credits (disc 2), ''[[George Harrison: Living in the Material World]]'' DVD. [[Roadshow Entertainment]], 2011; produced by Olivia Harrison, Nigel Sinclair & Martin Scorsese; directed by Martin Scorsese.</ref> and supplied personal reminisces and family photographs for [[Olivia Harrison]]'s book of the same title.<ref>Olivia Harrison, pp. 258\u201359, 398.</ref>\n\nIn 2010 and 2011, Wright toured again with Ringo Starr & His All-Starr Band.<ref name=\"RingoSiteBio\" /> Following a summer 2011 tour of Europe with Starr, Wright participated in the Hippiefest US tour with artists such as [[Felix Cavaliere]], [[Mark Farner]], [[Dave Mason]] and [[Rick Derringer]],<ref name=\"Voger/Hippiefest\" /> before returning to Europe for shows with his own band late that year.<ref name=\"vonBF/dprp\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nWright resides in [[Palos Verdes Estates, California]] with wife Rose, whom he married in 1985.<ref name=\"vonBF/dprp\" /> He was previously married to Christina,<ref>Badman, p. 79.</ref> who, as Tina Wright, received co-writing credits on Wright's songs \"I'm Alive\" (from ''The Mirror''),<ref name=\"TheMirror sleeve\">[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=1446303 Sleeve credits], ''The Mirror'' LP. [[Island Records]], 1974; produced by Gary Wright, Mick Jones & Eddie Kramer.</ref> \"Feel for Me\" (''The Dream Weaver'')<ref name=\"DreamWeaverSleeve\" /> and \"I'm the One Who'll Be by Your Side\" (''Headin' Home'').<ref name=\"Viglione/Home\">{{cite web|title=Gary Wright ''Headin' Home''|author=Viglione, Joe |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/headin-home-mw0000371772|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 19, 2014}}</ref> He has two adult sons, Dorian and Justin.<ref name=\"vonBF/dprp\" /> Justin is a member of the band Intangible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intangiblemusic.com/ |title=Intangible |publisher=intangiblemusic.com |date= |accessdate=November 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWright has spoken out on the importance of creative opportunities for children in the public educational system,<ref name=\"TheSound\" /> and expressed his opposition to the prevalence of free [[music download]]ing and its disadvantage to artists.<ref name=\"Barnes Interview\" /> In 2008, he voiced his support for [[Barack Obama]]'s [[2008 United States presidential election|presidential campaign]], during which \"Dream Weaver\" was a song adopted for the [[Democratic National Convention]] in [[Denver, Colorado]].<ref name=\"Klein/HuffPost\">{{cite web|title='Dream Weaver' \u2013 Why Gary Wright Backs Barack Obama|author=Klein, Howie |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/howie-klein/dream-weaver---why-gary-w_b_124674.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=September 7, 2008|accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref> That year, Wright discussed the message behind \"Dream Weaver\" with ''[[The Huffington Post|Huffington Post]]'' writer and political activist [[Howie Klein]], saying: \"With ''Wayne's World'' and all that, the perception of the song's meaning got a little bit changed for a lot of people. It's a very spiritual song. 'Dream Weaver' is really a song whose lyrical content is about the consciousness of the Universe: God moving us through the night \u2013 delusion and suffering \u2013 into the Higher Realms.\"<ref name=\"Klein/HuffPost\" />\n\nIn August 2014, Wright announced the imminent publication of his autobiography, ''Dream Weaver: Music, Meditation, and My Friendship with George Harrison''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Wright to reveal all about George Harrison friendship in new book|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/showbiz/498772/Gary-Wright-to-reveal-all-about-George-Harrison-friendship-in-new-book|work=[[Daily Express]]|date=August 13, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref> Coinciding with the book's release, Wright's Warner Bros. albums were reissued for digital download.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/08/27/dream-weaver-singer-gary-wright-weaves-life-story-in-oct-14-memoir/14658587/|title=Gary Wright's 'Dream Weaver' memoir out Oct. 2|last=Gundersen|first=Edna|date=August 27, 2014|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* 1970 ''Extraction'' (1970)\n* 1971 ''[[Footprint (album)|Footprint]]'' (1971)\n* 1975 ''[[The Dream Weaver]]'' (1975) [[Billboard 200|US]] #7 - US: Gold<ref name=\"Gold & Platinum\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/|title=Gold & Platinum|website=RIAA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n* 1977 ''[[The Light of Smiles]]'' (1977) US #23\n* 1977 ''[[Touch and Gone]]'' (1977) US #117\n* 1979 ''[[Headin' Home album|Headin' Home]]'' (1979) US #147\n* 1981 ''The Right Place'' (1981) US #79\n* 1988 ''Who I Am'' (1988)\n* 1995 ''First Signs of Life'' (1995)\n* 1999 ''Human Love''\n* 2008 ''Waiting to Catch the Light'' \n* 2010 ''Connected''\n\n===Collaborations===\n* 1972 ''That Was Only Yesterday'' (with Spooky Tooth)\n* 1972 ''Ring of Changes'' (with Wonderwheel)\n* 2004 ''Down This Road'' (Gary Wright & Leah Weiss)\n\n===Soundtracks===\n* 1974 ''Benjamin \u2013 The Original Soundtrack of Willy Bogner's Motion Picture''\n* 1986 ''Fire and Ice'' (soundtrack )\n\n===Compilations===\n* 1998 ''The Best of Gary Wright: The Dream Weaver'' \n* 2003 ''The Essentials''\n* 2017 ''Greatest Hits''\n\n===Extended play===\n* ''The Light of a Million Suns'' (2008)\n\n===Singles===\n{{Expand list|date=June 2015}}\n{{BLP sources section|date=June 2015}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=center rowspan=2|Year\n!align=center rowspan=2|Song\n!align=center colspan=4|Peak chart positions (U.S.)\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Certification\n!align=center rowspan=2|Album\n|-\n!width=60|<small>[[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]</small>\n!width=60|<small>[[Adult Contemporary (chart)|''Billboard'' A/C]]</small>\n!width=60|<small>[[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|U.S.<br/>R&B]]</small>\n!width=60|<small>[[Mainstream rock|U.S.<br/>Rock]]</small>\n|-\n|align=left valign=center rowspan=2|1971\n|align=left valign=top|\"Get on the Right Road\"\n|align=ce